  "ancestors": [
    {
      "code": "ofs",
      "role": "parent",
      "weight": 0.82,
      "notes": "Descent from Old Frisian via the North Frisian branch. Diverged from Old Frisian after the 13th century when Frisian speakers settled on the North Frisian Islands and mainland Schleswig."
    },
    {
      "code": "da",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.07,
      "notes": "Danish adstrate: North Frisia was under Danish sovereignty until 1864 (Second Schleswig War). Danish administrative language and bilingualism strongly influenced North Frisian phonology and lexicon."
    },
    {
      "code": "nds",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.06,
      "notes": "Low German adstrate: North Frisia sits within the Low German dialect area. Heavy Low German lexical influence, especially after the Hanseatic period."
    },
    {
      "code": "de-DE",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.05,
      "notes": "Standard German adstrate: dominant language since 1864; all North Frisians are bilingual in German. Ongoing influence on vocabulary and syntax."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "North Frisian (Nordfriisk / Frasch / Freesk) — spoken by ~8,000–10,000 speakers in Nordfriesland (Schleswig-Holstein, Germany). Severely endangered. Comprises ~10 distinct dialect groups divided into insular (Söl'ring, Fering, Öömrang, Halunder) and mainland (Mooring, Goesharde, Wiedingharde, Karrharde, etc.) varieties. Recognized as a regional minority language by Germany under the European Charter for Regional/Minority Languages. KEY FEATURES: (1) CENTRING DIPHTHONGS /iə, uə, yə/ — shared Frisian heritage with West Frisian. (2) FINAL DEVOICING as in West Frisian and Dutch. (3) VOICED STOP /ɡ/ — retained from Old Frisian (not the Dutch/LG fricative). (4) RICH VOWEL SYSTEM: up to 20 vowel phonemes in some dialects (front rounded ö, ü, öö, üü). (5) /tʃ, dʒ/ affricates — more productive than in West Frisian. (6) DANISH INFLUENCE: prosodic patterns and some lexicon from centuries of Danish rule. (7) Extreme dialect diversity — mainland and island varieties are often mutually unintelligible. The Mooring dialect (mainland) and Fering (Föhr island) are among the best documented. Sources: Walker & Wilts (2001), Århammar (2001), Fort & Munske (2001).",
